            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.18231/2606.18231v1/x15.png",
                "caption": "Figure 5:Simulating Gaussian Splats and Meshes at Scale.We show an elastodynamic simulation of a Gaussian Splat and a mesh scene with objects given mechanical properties generated byAdaVoMP. We find that objects like the sofa and the pillows on the sofa are stable under gravity. Near the center of the scene, we simulate a robot(frankaemika,2025)which interacts with the fruits on the table producing realistic interactions. We integrateAdaVoMPinto RoboLab(Yanget al.,2026)to generate this demo. The Gaussian Splat is generated with Marble(World Labs,2025)and the robot is controlled by theπ0.5\\pi_{0.5}(Blacket al.,2025)Vision-Language-Action model (: 04:27).",
                "position": 3193
            }
        ]
    },
    {
        "header": "Appendix AAdditional Results",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.18231/2606.18231v1/x18.png",
                "caption": "Figure 6:Scaling Model, Training, and Test-time Compute.Left / Center:We visualize the best runs of our sparse adaptive model across three independent axes: training tokens, test-time compute (output resolution), and model size.\nWe show displacement errors for Poisson’s ratio (ν\\nu) and Young’s modulus (EE) as a function of training tokens, showing that larger models achieve lower error at a fixed training budget and that allocating additional test-time compute (higher resolution) consistently improves accuracy.Right:We show the final training budget and show the error trend as a function of resolution (top) and model size (bottom).",
                "position": 3438
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.18231/2606.18231v1/x19.png",
                "caption": "Figure 7:Memory Scaling.Peak GPU memory usage versus resolution.\nWe observe a sub-quadratic scaling relationship ofM∝N1.35M\\propto N^{1.35}.\nThis efficient scaling allows for the generation of high-resolution102431024^{3}volumes within the memory constraints of standard hardware (e.g., 8×\\timesA100, dashed orange line).\nThe curves for different model sizes remain parallel, suggesting that the memory overhead from model parameters is independent of the resolution-based scaling.",
                "position": 3445
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.18231/2606.18231v1/x20.png",
                "caption": "Figure 8:Effective Dimensionality of Adaptive Geometry.Active voxel count as a function of resolution for varying sparsity thresholds.\nThe slope of these curves represents the dimensionddof the generated geometry.\nWe measure an effective dimensionality ofd≈2.48d\\approx 2.48for our sparse adaptive volumetric geometry, which falls between surface scaling (d=2d=2) and dense volumetric scaling (d=3d=3). In some cases,SAVcan represent a volume more efficiently than representing the same object’s surface as a dense voxel grid.",
                "position": 3453
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.18231/2606.18231v1/x21.png",
                "caption": "Figure 9:Parameter versus Resolution Sensitivity.Left:Total FLOPs as a function of model parameters for various resolutions.Top Right:Resolution scaling for the Huge (665M) model.Bottom Right:Parameter scaling at fixed102431024^{3}resolution.\nWe find that computational cost scales linearly with parameters (F∝P1.00F\\propto P^{1.00}), whereas it scales super-quadratically with resolution (F∝N2.32F\\propto N^{2.32}).\nThe vertical stratification in the left plot confirms that resolution is the dominant driver of compute; increasing model size from 69M to 665M increases cost by roughly10×10\\times, whereas increasing resolution from1283128^{3}to102431024^{3}increases cost by two orders of magnitude.",
                "position": 3460
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.18231/2606.18231v1/x22.png",
                "caption": "Figure 10:Compute-memory Pareto Frontier.Computational cost (FLOPs) versus peak memory usage.\nThe Pareto frontier shows the optimal trade-off between compute and memory.Insets:At mid-compute budgets (lower-right inset,1283128^{3}regime), a model larger thanHachieves1.4×1.4\\timesmore TFLOPs per GB compared to smaller models.\nAt high-compute budgets (upper-left inset,102431024^{3}regime), scaling from theSto larger thanHmodel yields43×43\\timesmore FLOPs for only20×20\\timesmore memory.",
                "position": 3469
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2606.18231/2606.18231v1/x23.png",
                "caption": "Figure 11:First:We show realistic simulations for 18 Gaussian Splats falling through a pachinko machine mesh using generated properties (: 04:44).Second:We show realistic simulations for meshes using predicted material values (: 04:57).Third:In this example, we applyAdaVoMPto this Gaussian Splat model that we captured using a commercial app. Our method converts this model into a simulation-ready asset, which is tetmeshed and simulated with FEM (: 04:57).Fourth:We show realistic simulations for meshes using predicted material values (: 04:44).",
                "position": 3485
            },
